\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
The Structure Theory of Complete Local Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)$
\end_inset

 be a complete local field.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 contains a field.
 Then there exists a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}\subset A$
\end_inset

 such that the composite map 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}\subseteq A\to A/\mathfrak{m}=K$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K_{0}\oplus_{K_{0}}\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces, and we may identify 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
coefficient field
\series default
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The choice of a coefficient field 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not unique 
\emph default
in general, although in positive prime characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 it is unique if 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is perfect, which is a bit surprising.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)$
\end_inset

 that contains a field is called 
\series bold
equicharacteristic
\series default
, because 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 contains a field if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 have the same characteristic.
 (It is clear that if 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq A$
\end_inset

, then they must have the same characteristic.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must have characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 too, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 contains a copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Since no nonzero integer vanishes in 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, every nonzero integer is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, which gives a map of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}:=(\mathbb{Z}\backslash\{0\})^{-1}\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by the universal mapping property of localization.
 On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has positive prime characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p>0$
\end_inset

, it clearly contains a copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Local rings that are not equicharacteristic are called 
\series bold
mixed characteristic
\series default
.
 The characteristic of the residue class field of such a ring is always
 a positive prime integer 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The characteristic of the ring is either 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, which is what it will be in the domain case, or else a power of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $k>1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
discrete valuation ring
\series default
, abbreviated DVR, is a local domain 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, not a field, whose maximal ideal is principal.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is easily shown that in a DVR, every nonzero element of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is uniquely expressible in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $ut^{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a unit, and every ideal is consequently principal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathbb{R}[t]_{\langle t^{2}+1\rangle}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle t^{2}+1\rangle\mathbb{R}[t]_{\langle t^{2}+1\rangle}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a DVR.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a local domain which is not a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is principal.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an example of a local ring that contains a field but does not contain
 a coefficient field.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $V/\mathfrak{m}\cong\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq\mathbb{R}(t)$
\end_inset

 does not contain any element whose square is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

: the square of a non-constant rational function is non-constant, and the
 square of a real scalar cannot be 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hensel's Lemma and coefficient fields in equal characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Hensel's Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)$
\end_inset

 be a complete local ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a monic polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}$
\end_inset

 denotes the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in A[x]$
\end_inset

 under the ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x]\to K[x]$
\end_inset

 induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $A\to K$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}=GH$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $G,H\in K[x]$
\end_inset

 are monic of degrees 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x]$
\end_inset

, then there are unique monic polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in A[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=gh$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}=G$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{h}=H$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset

 denote the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(A/\mathfrak{m}^{n})[x]$
\end_inset

.
 We recursively construct monic polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n}\in(A/\mathfrak{m}^{n})[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}\in(A/\mathfrak{m}^{n})[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}=G_{n}H_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}$
\end_inset

 reduce to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, respectively, mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, and show that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n}$
\end_inset

 are unique.
 Note that it will follow that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n}$
\end_inset

 has the same degree as 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}$
\end_inset

 has the same degree as 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s+t=d$
\end_inset

.
 The uniqueness implies that mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{n-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}$
\end_inset

 become 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n-1}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 This yields that the sequence of coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\longleftarrow n}(A/\mathfrak{m}^{n})=A,
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is complete.
 Using the coefficient determined in this way, we get a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x]$
\end_inset

, monic of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we get a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x]$
\end_inset

, monic of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}=G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{h}=H$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=gh$
\end_inset

, since this holds mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

: thus, every coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $f-gh$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{n}\mathfrak{m}^{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It remains to carry through the recursion, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1}=G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}=H$
\end_inset

 from the hypothesis of the theorem.
 Now assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}$
\end_inset

 have been constructed and shown unique for a certain 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 We must construct 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and show that they are unique as well.
 It will be convenient to work mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 in the rest of the argument: replace 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{m}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Construct 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{*}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x]$
\end_inset

 by lifting each coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}$
\end_inset

 respectively, but such that the two leading coefficients occur in degrees
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 respectively and are both 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Then, mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F\equiv G^{*}H^{*}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=F-G^{*}H^{*}\in\mathfrak{m}^{n}A[x]$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that there are unique choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\in\mathfrak{m}^{n}A[x]$
\end_inset

 of degree at most 
\begin_inset Formula $s-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\in\mathfrak{m}^{n}A[x]$
\end_inset

 of degree at most 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F-(G^{*}+\delta)(H^{*}+\varepsilon)=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\varepsilon G^{*}+\delta H^{*}+\delta\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta,\varepsilon\in\mathfrak{m}^{n}A[x]$
\end_inset

, their product is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{2n}A[x]=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus our problem is to find such 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\varepsilon G^{*}+\delta H^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 generate the unit ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x]_{\text{red}}=K[x]$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{*}$
\end_inset

 generate the unit ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x]$
\end_inset

, and so we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\alpha G^{*}+\beta H^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\Delta\alpha G^{*}+\Delta\beta H^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\beta$
\end_inset

 are in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{n}A[x]$
\end_inset

, but do not yet satisfy our degree requirements.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{*}$
\end_inset

 is monic, we can divide 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\alpha$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{*}$
\end_inset

 to get a quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and remainder 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\alpha=\gamma H^{*}+\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 If we consider this mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $0\equiv\gamma H_{n}+\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, from which it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma,\varepsilon\in\mathfrak{m}^{n}A[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\varepsilon G^{*}+\delta H^{*}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\gamma G^{*}+\Delta\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon G^{*}$
\end_inset

 both have degree 
\begin_inset Formula $<n$
\end_inset

, so does 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta H^{*}$
\end_inset

, which implies that the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq s-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, suppose that we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\varepsilon'G^{*}+\delta'H^{*}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon'$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq t-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta'$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq s-1$
\end_inset

.
 Subtracting, we get an equation 
\begin_inset Formula $0=\mu G^{*}+\nu H^{*}$
\end_inset

 where the degree 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\varepsilon-\varepsilon'$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq t-1$
\end_inset

 and the degree 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\delta-\delta'$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq s-1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{*}$
\end_inset

 is a unit considered mod 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{*}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\in\langle H^{*}\rangle$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{*}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{*}$
\end_inset

 is monic, and so this cannot happen unless 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

: the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is too small.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We summarize some of the formulas used in the proof above:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1 & =\alpha G^{*}+\beta H^{*}\\
\Delta & =F-G^{*}H^{*}\\
\alpha\Delta & =\gamma H^{*}+\varepsilon\\
\delta & =\gamma G^{*}+\beta\Delta.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)=(\mathbb{Z}_{3},\langle3\rangle,\mathbb{F}_{3})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathbb{Z}_{3}[x]$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}-7$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\equiv(x+2)(x+1)\text{ mod }3
\]

\end_inset

We want to lift 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1}(x):=x+2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}(x):=x+1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\equiv G_{2}(x)H_{2}(x)\text{ mod }9.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We calculate all the ingredients used in the proof above:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G^{*} & =x+2\\
H^{*} & =x+1\\
F & =x^{2}+2\\
\Delta & =6x\\
\alpha & =1\\
\beta & =-1\\
\gamma & =6\\
\varepsilon & =3\\
\delta & =3.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

From this, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{2}(x)=x+5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}(x)=x+4$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Keep in mind that lifts 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in\mathbb{Z}_{3}[x]$
\end_inset

 depends on the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathbb{Z}_{3}[x]$
\end_inset

, and not on 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1},H_{2}\in\mathbb{F}_{3}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathbb{Z}_{3}[x]$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=x^{2}-4$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r(x)\equiv G_{1}(x)H_{1}(x)\text{ mod }3,
\]

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\not\equiv G_{2}(x)H_{2}(x)\text{ mod }9$
\end_inset

.
 Instead we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r(x)\equiv\widetilde{G_{2}}(x)\widetilde{H_{2}}(x)\text{ mod }9,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{G_{2}}(x)=x+2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{H_{2}}(x)=x+7$
\end_inset

.
 The fact that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\equiv G_{1}(x)H_{1}(x)\equiv r(x)\text{ mod }3
\]

\end_inset

tells us that the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 are somewhat 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

close
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to each other.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)=(\mathbb{Z}_{3},\langle3\rangle,\mathbb{F}_{3})$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{4}-7x^{3}+2x^{2}+2x+1\in\mathbb{Z}_{3}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\equiv(x+1)^{2}(x^{2}+1)\text{ mod }3.
\]

\end_inset

We want to lift 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1}(x):=x^{2}+2x+1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}(x):=x^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\equiv G_{2}(x)H_{2}(x)\text{ mod }9.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Working mod 
\begin_inset Formula $9$
\end_inset

, we calculate all the ingredients used in the proof above:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G^{*} & =x^{2}+2x+1\\
H^{*} & =x^{2}+1\\
F & =x^{4}+2x^{3}+2x^{2}+2x+1\\
\Delta & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=0$
\end_inset

, so we don't need to calculate anything else: We have 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{2}(x)=G_{1}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}(x)=H_{1}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Now let's lift 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{3}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}(x)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\equiv G_{3}(x)H_{3}(x)\text{ mod }27.
\]

\end_inset

Working mod 
\begin_inset Formula $27$
\end_inset

, we calculate all the ingredients used in the proof above:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G^{*} & =x^{2}+2x+1\\
H^{*} & =x^{2}+1\\
F & =x^{4}+20x^{3}+2x^{2}+2x+1\\
\Delta & =18x^{3}\\
\alpha & =13x\\
\beta & =14x+1\\
\gamma & =18x^{2}+9\\
\varepsilon & =18\\
\delta & =18x+9.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{3}(x)=x^{2}+20x+10$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}(x)=x^{2}+19$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)=(\mathbb{C}[[t]],\langle t\rangle,\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}-(1+t)\in\mathbb{C}[[t]][x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\equiv(x-1)(x+1)\text{ mod }\langle t\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

We want to lift 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1}(x):=x-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}(x):=x+1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\equiv G_{2}(x)H_{2}(x)\text{ mod }\langle t^{2}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We calculate all the ingredients used in the proof above:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G^{*} & =x-1\\
H^{*} & =x+1\\
F & =x^{2}-(1+t)\\
\Delta & =-t\\
\alpha & =-\frac{1}{2}\\
\beta & =\frac{1}{2}\\
\gamma & =0\\
\varepsilon & =\frac{1}{2}t\\
\delta & =-\frac{1}{2}t.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

From this, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{2}(x)=x-1-\frac{1}{2}t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}(x)=x+1+\frac{1}{2}t$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)=(\mathbb{Z}_{3},\langle3\rangle,\mathbb{F}_{3})$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}-7$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}(x)\equiv G(x)H(x)$
\end_inset

 mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle3\rangle$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $G(x)=x+2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H(x)=x+1$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[x]$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x+2)-(x+1)=1$
\end_inset

 for example.
 Thus, Hensel's lemma guarentees that there are two polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x),h(x)\in\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}(x)=G(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{h}(x)=H(x)$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x)=x+(2,5,14,\dots)\quad\text{and}\quad h(x)=x+(1,4,13,\dots).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)=(\mathbb{Z}_{3},\langle3\rangle,\mathbb{F}_{3})$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{4}-7x^{3}+2x^{2}+2x+1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}(x)\equiv G(x)H(x)$
\end_inset

 mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle3\rangle$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $G(x)=(x+1)^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H(x)=x^{2}+1$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, Hensel's lemma guarentees that there are two polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x),h(x)\in\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}(x)=G(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{h}(x)=H(x)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, we can actually do better.
 It turns out that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x) & =\left(x^{2}+(2,2,20,\dots)x+(1,1,10,\dots)\right)\left(x^{2}+(1,1,1,\dots)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=(x-(2,5,23,\dots))(x-(2,2,11,\dots))(x^{2}+(1,1,1,\dots))=\left(x^{2}+(2,2,20,\dots)x+(1,1,10,\dots)\right))(x-(2,11,92,\dots))(x^{2}+(1,1,1,\dots))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)=(\mathbb{R}[[t]],\langle t\rangle,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}-t-1$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\equiv(x-1)(x+1)\text{ mod }\langle t\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

In fact, this lifts to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\left(x-\left(1,1+\frac{t}{2},1+\frac{t}{2}-\frac{t^{2}}{8},\dots\right)\right)\left(x+\left(1,1+\frac{t}{2},1+\frac{t}{2}-\frac{t^{2}}{8},\dots\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coefficient fields in equal characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)$
\end_inset

 be a complete local ring that contains a field of characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has a coefficient field.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 will contain a maximal subfield, and any such subfield is a coefficient
 field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all subrings of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which happen to be fields.
 By hypothesis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 Given a chain of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, the union is again a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that is a field.
 By Zorn's Lemma, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 will have a maximal element 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 To complete the proof of the theorem, we shall show that 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

 maps isomorphically onto 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Obviously, we have a map 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}\subset A\to A/\mathfrak{m}=K$
\end_inset

, so we have a map 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}\to K$
\end_inset

.
 This map is automatically injective: call the image 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 To complete the proof, it suffices to show that it is surjective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If not, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 not in the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We consider two cases: the first is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is transcendental over 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 denote an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is a lift of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}[t]$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and every nonzero element is a unit: if some element were in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, then working mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, we would get an equation of algebraic dependence for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K_{0}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 By the universal mapping property of localization, the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}[t]\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 extends to a map 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}(t)\subseteq A$
\end_inset

, which is necessarily an inclusion.
 This yields a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

, a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a lift the corresponding polynomial with coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}[x]\subseteq A[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, this polynomial factors as 
\begin_inset Formula $(x-\theta)H(x)$
\end_inset

, where these are relatively prime because 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K_{0}}$
\end_inset

: this is the only place in the argument where we use that the field has
 characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 The factorization lifts uniquely: we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(x-t)h(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in A$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $t\equiv\theta$
\end_inset

 mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, the isomorphisms
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{0}[t]\cong K_{0}[x]/\langle f\rangle\cong\overline{K_{0}}[x]/\langle f_{\theta}\rangle\cong K_{0}[\theta]
\]

\end_inset

implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}[t]$
\end_inset

 is a field contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that is strictly larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

, a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Coefficient fields in characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 when the residue class field is perfect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We can get a similar result easily in characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p>0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $K=A/\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is perfect, although the proof is completely different.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Perfect Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we recall some basic facts about perfect fields.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
perfect 
\series default
if every irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Every field of characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is perfect.
 We will see that finite fields are perfect too.
 The simplest example of a nonperfect field is the rational function field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}(u)$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}-u$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}(u)[X]$
\end_inset

 but not separable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that for an irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

, it is inseparable if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(X)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Here is the standard way to check a field is perfect:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremperfectifandonlyif}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is perfect if and only if it has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, or it has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{p}=K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, any irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 is separable since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(X)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show when 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 that every irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{p}=K$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we will show the 
\emph on
negations 
\emph default
are equivalent: An inseparable irreducible exists in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{p}\neq K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{p}\neq K$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K\backslash K^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}-a$
\end_inset

 has only one root in a splitting field: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p}=a$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}-a=X^{p}-\alpha^{p}=(X-\alpha)^{p}$
\end_inset

 since we are working in characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}-a$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 too: any nontrivial proper monic factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}-a$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(X-\alpha)^{m}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq m\leq p-1$
\end_inset

.
 The coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{m-1}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X-\alpha)^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $-m\alpha$
\end_inset

, so if 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}-a$
\end_inset

 has a nontrivial proper factor in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $-m\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p-1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{F}_{p}^{\times}\subset K^{\times}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\alpha^{p}\in K^{p}$
\end_inset

, a contradiction.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}-a$
\end_inset

 is irreducible and inseparable in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose there is an inseparable irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(X)=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}$
\end_inset

, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(X)=a_{m}X^{pm}+a_{m-1}X^{p(m-1)}+\cdots+a_{1}X^{p}+a_{0}\in K[X^{p}].
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{p}=K$
\end_inset

, then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=b_{i}^{p}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}\in K$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(X)=(b_{m}X^{m}+b_{m-1}X^{(m-1)}+\cdots+b_{1}X+b_{0})^{p}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, we have a contradiction, which shows 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{p}\neq K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Fields of characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and finite fields are perfect.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremperfectifandonlyif})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, fields of characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 are perfect.
 It remains to show a finite field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{p}=K$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power map 
\begin_inset Formula $K\to K$
\end_inset

 is injective, and therefore surjective because 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is finite, so we are done.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is perfect if and only if every finite extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a separable extension.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is perfect: every irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L/K$
\end_inset

 is a finite extension, then the minimal polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 of every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, and therefore separble, so 
\begin_inset Formula $L/K$
\end_inset

 is a separable extension.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose every finite field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a separable extension.
 To show 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is perfect, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

 be irreducible.
 Consider the field 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This field is a finite extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, so a separable extension by hypothesis, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, it is a separable polynomial.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coefficient fields in characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 when the residue class field is perfect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},K)$
\end_inset

 be a complete local ring of positive prime characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is perfect.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{p^{n}}=\left\{ a^{p^{n}}\mid a\in A\right\} $
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}=\bigcap_{n=0}^{\infty}A^{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is a coefficient field for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and it is the only coefficient field for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First we show 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}\cap\mathfrak{m}=0$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in K_{0}\cap\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, so for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u=v^{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 too, so 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\bigcap_{n=0}^{\infty}\mathfrak{m}^{p^{n}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 consists of units in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $u=v^{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $1/u=(1/v)^{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the inverse of every nonzero element of 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

 is clearly a ring (since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

), it is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, we want to show that given 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in K$
\end_inset

 some element of 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 denote an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{1/p^{n}}\in K$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is perfect).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}^{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t_{n}^{p^{n}}\right\} _{n}$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and so has a limit 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n+1}^{p}$
\end_inset

 both map to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{1/p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}-t_{n+1}^{p}$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 powers, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{n}^{p^{n}}-t_{n+1}^{p^{n+1}}\in\mathfrak{m}^{p^{n}}.
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the sequence is Cauchy, and has a limit 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in A$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 (The quotient map 
\begin_inset Formula $A\to A/\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is continuous, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 has the discrete topology and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

-adic topology).
 Therefore, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in A^{p^{k}}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 But
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{k},t_{k+1}^{p},\dots,t_{k+h}^{p^{h}},\dots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is a sequence of the same sort for the element 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{1/p^{k}}$
\end_inset

, and so is Cauchy and has a limit 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{k}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{k}^{p^{k}}=t$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in A^{p^{k}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally we prove uniqueness.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is another coefficient field for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=L^{p}=\cdots=L^{p^{n}}=\cdots,
\]

\end_inset

and so for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L\subseteq L^{p^{n}}\subseteq A^{p^{n}}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $L\subseteq K_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $L\cong K\cong K_{0}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Coefficient fields and structure theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Before pursuing the issue of the existence of coefficient fields and coefficient
 rings further, we show that the existence of a coefficient field implies
 that the ring is a homomorphic image of a power series ring in finitely
 many variables over a field, and is also a module-finite extension of such
 a ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we can put a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 called the 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-adic topology.
 The basic open sets in this topology are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x,k}=x+I^{k}M$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $k,\ell\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\geq k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Then it's easy to show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{x,k}\cap U_{y,\ell}=\begin{cases}
U_{x,k} & \text{if }x\equiv y\text{ mod }I^{k}M\\
\emptyset & \text{else. }
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also easy to show that this topological space is separated (also known
 as Hausdorff) if and only if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcap_{n=0}^{\infty}I^{n}M=0.
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be separated and complete in the 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-adic topology, where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-adically separated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{h}\in M$
\end_inset

 have images that span 
\begin_inset Formula $M/IM$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $A/I$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{h}$
\end_inset

 spans 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M=Au_{1}+\cdots Au_{h}+IM$
\end_inset

, we find that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I^{n}M=I^{n}u_{1}+\cdots+I^{n}u_{n}+I^{n+1}M.\label{eq:recursiveformula1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 be given.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 can be written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{01}u_{1}+\cdots+a_{0h}u_{h}+v_{1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}\in IM$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}=a_{11}u_{1}+\cdots+a_{1h}u_{h}+v_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1j}\in IM$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}\in I^{2}M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=(a_{01}+a_{11})u_{1}+\cdots+(a_{0h}+a_{1h})u_{h}+v_{2}.
\]

\end_inset

By a straightforward induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 we obtain, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=(a_{01}+a_{11}+\cdots+a_{n1})u_{1}+\cdots+(a_{0h}+a_{1h}+\cdots+a_{nh})u_{h}+v_{n+1},
\]

\end_inset

where every 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{jk}\in I^{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n+1}\in I^{n+1}M$
\end_inset

.
 In the recursive step, the formula 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:recursiveformula1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is applied to the element 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n+1}\in I^{n+1}M$
\end_inset

.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}a_{jk}$
\end_inset

 represents an element 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{k}$
\end_inset

 of the complete ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=s_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+s_{h}u_{h}.
\]

\end_inset

The point is that if we subtract
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a_{01}+a_{11}+\cdots+a_{n1})u_{1}+\cdots+(a_{0h}+a_{1h}+\cdots+a_{nh})u_{n}
\]

\end_inset

from 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n+1}\in I^{n+1}M$
\end_inset

, and if we subtract it from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+s_{h}u_{h},
\]

\end_inset

we also get an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{n+1}M$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u-(s_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+s_{h}u_{h})\in\bigcap_{n}I^{n+1}M=0,
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-adically separated.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We tacitly used in the argument above that if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{jk}\in I^{j}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j\geq n+1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n+1,k}+a_{n+2,k}+\cdots+a_{n+t,k}+\cdots\in I^{n+1}.
\]

\end_inset

This actually requires an argument.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated by the monomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 in the generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n+1+t,k}=\sum_{\nu=1}^{d}q_{t\nu}g_{\nu},
\]

\end_inset

with every 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{t\nu}\in I^{t}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}a_{n+1+t,k}=\sum_{\nu=1}^{d}\left(\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}q_{t\nu}\right)g_{\nu}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism, and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

-adically complete and separated for an ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 maps into 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a unique induced homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{A}^{I}\to B$
\end_inset

 that is continuous (i.e.
 preserves limits of Cauchy sequences in the appropriate ideal-adic topology).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{A}^{I}$
\end_inset

 is the ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-adic Cauchy sequences mod the ideal of sequences that converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 The continuity condition forces the element represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{n}\}_{n}$
\end_inset

 to map to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\varphi(a_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

(Cauchy sequences map to Cauchy sequences: if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{m}-a_{n}\in I^{N}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a_{m})-\varphi(a_{n})\in J^{N}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(I)\subseteq J$
\end_inset

).
 It is trivial to check that this is a ring homomorphism that kills the
 ideal of Cauchy sequences that converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, which gives the required map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{A}^{I}\to B$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
